04038nam a22006375i 9780292794078DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212008txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927940787 a10.7560/7183192doi  a(DE-B1597)588502  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aF1219.56.T46bD54 2008eb 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a972/.022221 aDiel, Lori Boornazian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Tira de Tepechpan :bNegotiating Place under Aztec and Spanish Rule /cLori Boornazian Diel. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (186 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction -- t2. The Tira de Tepechpan: -- t3. Pre-Imperial History -- t4. Imperial History -- t5. Colonial History of Painter A -- t6. Colonial Histories of Painters B, C, and D -- t7. The Alphabetic Annotations -- t8. Indigenous Histories as Strategies for Survival -- tAppendix. Transcription and Translation of Annotator 1’s Glosses -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCreated in Tepechpan, a relatively minor Aztec city in Central Mexico, the Tira de Tepechpan records important events in the city's history from 1298 through 1596. Most of the history is presented pictographically. A line of indigenous year signs runs the length of the Tira, with images above the line depicting events in Tepechpan and images below the line recording events at Tenochtitlan, capital of the Aztec empire and later the seat of Spanish rule. Written annotations amplify some of the images. In this volume, which includes color plates of the entire Tira, Lori Boornazian Diel investigates the motives behind the creation and modification of the Tira in the second half of the sixteenth century. She identifies the Tira's different contributors and reconciles their various histories by asking why these painters and annotators, working at different times, recorded the events that they did. Comparing the Tira to other painted histories from Central Mexico, Diel demonstrates that the main goal of the Tira was to establish the antiquity, autonomy, and prestige of Tepechpan among the Central Mexican city-states that vied for power and status in the preconquest and colonial worlds. Offering the unique point of view of a minor city with grand ambitions, this study of the Tira reveals imperial strategy from the grassroots up, showing how a subject city negotiated its position under Aztec and Spanish control.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAztec artzMexicozTepexpan. 0aAztecsxFirst contact with Europeans. 0aAztecszMexicozTepexpanxHistoryvChronology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/71831940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292794078423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292794078/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK